Scroll down for animations
This is a demo site for the grapesjs-plugins-scrollanimation. It allows you to create animations that will trigger when the user scrolls through your page. Feel free to play around with the website here, or import this plugin into your own project! To use this in your own plugin, check out the public repo on github.

Getting Started
To get started, drag the Scroll block from the blocks panel on the right into the canvas. All of the blocks can be dragged from the blocks panel into the the scroll block to apply animations to that block.Â 
By default, the scroll block will give you some sample content, but you can edit the content and the style to fit your needs. To edit the threshold to trigger for the scroll animation, click on the the gear icon in the top right corner. The animation can be edited in the style manager by clicking on the paintbrush in the top panel. The style manager is where you can select which classes to which you want your changes.
The animations trigger when the style classÂ  gjs-scroll-activeÂ is added to the html element, which happens when the user scrolls past a threshold. This means that if you want to edit the animation, you will need to edit the transition or transform with the class selected. The style classÂ  gjs-scroll-revealÂ alternatively, will be used when the user scrolls up. In the example above, the opacity is set to 0 and the element is moved down by the styles ofÂ  gjs-scroll-revealÂ until the user scrolls past the threshold. Once the user scrolls past the threshold, the styles ofÂ  gjs-scroll-activeÂ will set the opacity to 1 (so it can be seen) and move the element up.
To edit animations that will apply Â beforeÂ  the user hits the scroll threshold, select the classÂ  gjs-scroll-revealÂ in the style manager. You can then edit any of the attributes in the style manager, including the animation, which can be found underÂ  Extra.
To edit animations that will applyÂ  afterÂ  the user reaches the scroll threshold, select the classÂ  gjs-scroll-activeÂ in the style manager. These style changes will only apply as long as the user has passed the scroll threshold. If they scroll up, the element will be reset and the changes will take place again once the user scrolls down.Â
